2. G. Porzana (Spotted Gallinule).

There can be no doubt that the Spotted Gallinule breeds in the marshes of Norfolk. We have seen a considerable number of its eggs at Yarmouth, which, as well as its young, were found in the neighbourhood of that place. And we are also in pos- session of an egg taken from a female of this species which was killed in the marshes below Norwich.

3. G. ssaillonii (Baillon's Gallinule).

We have met with a specimen of this bird in the collection os Mr. Crickmore of Beccles, which was shot near that town. The throat, neck and belly are asli-colour; the sides and under 1311- coverts barred and spotted with black and white. The back is like that of the Spotted Gallinule; but this bird is con- siderably smaller than that species. An extremely small Galli- nule, probably of the above kind, was shot at Nacton in Suffolk many years since, and was in the possession of the late John Vernon, Esq.
